ACCIDENT HISTORY
There have been no accidental releases of ammonia at the Montevideo facility that resulted in deaths, injuries, property damage onsite, or known offsite deaths, injuries, property damage, or environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering-in-place.
EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM
The Montevideo facility has implemented a detailed written Emergency Response Plan (ERP).  The ERP is intended to address all emergencies at the facility, in addition to incidents related to a release of anhydrous ammonia.  The ERP includes:
Coordination with the local fire department and with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC);
Emergency escape procedures and emergency escape route assignments;
Procedures to be followed by employees who remain to operate critical plant operations before they evacuate;
Procedures to account for all employees after emergency evacuation has been completed;
What personal protective equipment and spill response equipment is available;
The preferred means of reporting fires and other emergencies;
Names of persons or departments who can be contacted for further information or explanation of duties under the plan;
Designation and training of a sufficient number of persons to assist in the safe and orderly evacuation of employees;
The names of personnel:  (1) responsible for maintenance of equipment and systems installed to prevent or control ignition, and (2) responsible for control of fuel source hazards;
Refers to other pertinent elements of the management system (i.e., standard operating procedures).
Jennie-O Turkey Store will continue to conduct operator training, and coordinate emergency response drills with the local fire department to improve ammonia safety and emergency response.
